"Zachos J.C., McCarren H., Murphy B., Röhl U., Westerhold T.","Tempo and scale of late Paleocene and early Eocene carbon isotope cycles: Implications for the origin of hyperthermals",2010,"Earth and Planetary Science Letters","299","1-2",,"242","249",,,10.1016/j.epsl.2010.09.004,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77958510951&partnerID=40&md5=b4a7be2b906741f3c38eebf9ad53ec09","Earth and Planetary Sciences Dept., University of California, Santa Cruz, CA 95064, United States; MARUM, Center for Marine Environmental Sciences, University of Bremen, Leobener Strasse, 28359 Bremen, Germany","Zachos, J.C., Earth and Planetary Sciences Dept., University of California, Santa Cruz, CA 95064, United States; McCarren, H., Earth and Planetary Sciences Dept., University of California, Santa Cruz, CA 95064, United States; Murphy, B., Earth and Planetary Sciences Dept., University of California, Santa Cruz, CA 95064, United States; Röhl, U., MARUM, Center for Marine Environmental Sciences, University of Bremen, Leobener Strasse, 28359 Bremen, Germany; Westerhold, T., MARUM, Center for Marine Environmental Sciences, University of Bremen, Leobener Strasse, 28359 Bremen, Germany","The upper Paleocene and lower Eocene are marked by several prominent (&gt;1‰) carbon isotope (δ13C) excursions (CIE) that coincide with transient global warmings, or thermal maxima, including the Paleocene-Eocene Thermal Maximum (PETM). The CIE, which are recorded mainly in marine sedimentary sequences, have also been identified in continental sequences, occurred episodically, and yet appear to be paced or triggered by orbital forcing. To constrain the timing and scale of the CIE relative to long-term baseline variability, we have constructed a 4.52million year (myr) long, high-resolution (~3kyr) bulk sediment carbon isotope record spanning the lower Eocene to upper Paleocene (C25r-C24n) from a pelagic sediment section recovered at ODP Site 1262 in the southeast Atlantic. This section, which was orbitally-tuned utilizing high-resolution core log physical property and geochemical records, is the most stratigraphically complete upper Paleocene to lower Eocene sequence recovered to date. Time-series analysis of the carbon isotope record along with a high-resolution Fe intensity record obtained by XRF core scanner reveal cyclicity with variance concentrated primarily in the precession (21kyr) and eccentricity bands (100 and 400-kyr) throughout the upper Paleocene-lower Eocene. In general, minima in δ13C correspond with peaks in Fe (i.e., carbonate dissolution), both of which appear to be in phase with maxima in eccentricity. This covariance is consistent with excess oceanic uptake of isotopically depleted carbon resulting in lower carbonate saturation during periods of high eccentricity. This relationship includes all late Paleocene and early Eocene CIE confirming pacing by orbital forcing. The lone exception is the PETM, which appears to be out of phase with the 400-kyr cycle, though possibly in phase with the 100-kyr cycle, reinforcing the notion that a mechanism other than orbital forcing and/or an additional source of carbon is required to account for the occurrence and unusual scale of this event. © 2010 Elsevier B.V.","Carbon cycle; Carbon isotopes; Eocene; Global warming; Paleocene; PETM","Carbon cycles; Carbon isotopes; Eocene; Paleocene; PETM; Analytical geochemistry; Dissolution; Global warming; Harmonic analysis; Sedimentology; Superalloys; Time series analysis; Isotopes; carbon cycle; carbon isotope; global warming; marine sediment; orbital forcing; Paleocene-Eocene boundary; paleoclimate; sediment core; sedimentary sequence; sequence stratigraphy",,,,,,"Agnini, C., An early Eocene carbon cycle perturbation at similar to 52.5Ma in the Southern Alps: chronology and biotic response (2009) Paleoceanography, 24; Archer, D., Buffett, B., Time-dependent response of the global ocean clathrate reservoir to climatic and anthropogenic forcing (2005) Geoche